[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Beyond machine learning, the principles of feature engineering are applied in various scientific fields, including physics.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] For example, physicists construct dimensionless numbers such as the Reynolds number in fluid dynamics, the Nusselt number in heat transfer, and the Archimedes number in sedimentation.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] They also develop first approximations of solutions, such as analytical solutions for the strength of materials in mechanics.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] One of the applications of feature engineering has been clustering of feature-objects or sample-objects in a dataset.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Especially, feature engineering based on matrix decomposition has been extensively used for data clustering under non-negativity constraints on the feature coefficients.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] These include *Non-Negative Matrix Factorization* (NMF), *Non-Negative Matrix-Tri Factorization* (NMTF), *Non-Negative Tensor Decomposition/Factorization* (NTF/NTD), etc.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] The non-negativity constraints on coefficients of the feature vectors mined by the above-stated algorithms yields a part-based representation, and different factor matrices exhibit natural clustering properties.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Several extensions of the above-stated feature engineering methods have been reported in literature, including *orthogonality-constrained factorization* for hard clustering, and *manifold learning* to overcome inherent issues with these algorithms.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Other classes of feature engineering algorithms include leveraging a common hidden structure across multiple inter-related datasets to obtain a consensus (common) clustering scheme.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] An example is *Multi-view Classification based on Consensus Matrix Decomposition* (MCMD), which mines a common clustering scheme across multiple datasets.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Coupled matrix and tensor decompositions are popular in multi-view feature engineering.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Feature engineering in machine learning and statistical modeling involves selecting, creating, transforming, and extracting data features.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Even relatively insignificant features may contribute to a model.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Feature selection can reduce the number of features to prevent a model from becoming too specific to the training data set (overfitting).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Feature explosion occurs when the number of identified features is too large for effective model estimation or optimization.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Feature explosion can be limited via techniques such as regularization, kernel methods, and feature selection.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Automation of feature engineering is a research topic that dates back to the 1990s.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Machine learning software that incorporates automated feature engineering has been commercially available since 2016.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Multi-relational Decision Tree Learning (MRDTL) extends traditional decision tree methods to relational databases, handling complex data relationships across tables.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] It innovatively uses selection graphs as decision nodes, refined systematically until a specific termination criterion is reached.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Most MRDTL studies base implementations on relational databases, which results in many redundant operations.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] These redundancies can be reduced by using techniques such as tuple id propagation.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] The deep feature synthesis (DFS) algorithm beat 615 of 906 human teams in a competition.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] The feature store is where the features are stored and organized for the explicit purpose of being used to either train models (by data scientists) or make predictions (by applications that have a trained model).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] A feature store includes the ability to store code used to generate features, apply the code to raw data, and serve those features to models upon request.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Useful capabilities include feature versioning and policies governing the circumstances under which features can be used.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Feature stores can be standalone software tools or built into machine learning platforms.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Feature engineering can be a time-consuming and error-prone process, as it requires domain expertise and often involves trial and error.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] Deep learning algorithms may be used to process a large raw dataset without having to resort to feature engineering.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] However, deep learning algorithms still require careful preprocessing and cleaning of the input data.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/feature-extraction] In addition, choosing the right architecture, hyperparameters, and optimization algorithm for a deep neural network can be a challenging and iterative process.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/keyword-extraction] Methods for automatic keyword extraction can be supervised, semi-supervised, or unsupervised.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/keyword-extraction] Unsupervised methods can be further divided into simple statistics, linguistics or graph-based, or ensemble methods that combine some or most of these methods.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/n-gram] An ***n*-gram** is a sequence of *n* adjacent symbols in a particular order.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/n-gram] The symbols may be *n* adjacent letters (including punctuation marks and blanks), syllables, or rarely whole words found in a language dataset; or adjacent phonemes extracted from a speech-recording dataset, or adjacent base pairs extracted from a genome.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/n-gram] They are collected from a text corpus or speech corpus.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/n-gram] If Latin numerical prefixes are used, then *n*-gram of size 1 is called a "unigram", size 2 a "bigram" (or, less commonly, a "digram") etc.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/n-gram] If, instead of the Latin ones, the English cardinal numbers are furtherly used, then they are called "four-gram", "five-gram", etc.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/n-gram] Similarly, Greek numerical prefixes such as "monomer", "dimer", "trimer", "tetramer", "pentamer", etc., or English cardinal numbers, "one-mer", "two-mer", "three-mer", etc. are used in computational biology for polymers or oligomers of a known size, called *k*-mers.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/n-gram] When the items are words, n-grams may also be called *shingles*.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/n-gram] In the context of natural language processing (NLP), the use of *n*-grams allows bag-of-words models to capture information such as word order, which would not be possible in the traditional bag of words setting.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/n-gram] In 1951, Shannon discussed *n*-gram models of English.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/n-gram] Figure 1 shows several example sequences and the corresponding 1-gram, 2-gram and 3-gram sequences.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/n-gram] Here are further examples; these are word-level 3-grams and 4-grams (and counts of the number of times they appeared) from the Google *n*-gram corpus.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] In corpus linguistics, **part-of-speech tagging** (**POS tagging**, **PoS tagging**, or **POST**), also called **grammatical tagging**, is the process of marking up a word in a text (corpus) as corresponding to a particular part of speech, based on both its definition and its context.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] A simplified form of this is commonly taught to school-age children, in the identification of words as nouns, verbs, adjectives, adverbs, etc.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Once performed by hand, POS tagging is now done in the context of computational linguistics, using algorithms which associate discrete terms, as well as hidden parts of speech, by a set of descriptive tags.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] POS-tagging algorithms fall into two distinctive groups: rule-based and stochastic.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Brill's tagger, one of the first and most widely used English POS taggers, employs rule-based algorithms.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Part-of-speech tagging is harder than just having a list of words and their parts of speech, because some words can represent more than one part of speech at different times, and because some parts of speech are complex.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] This is not rare—in natural languages (as opposed to many artificial languages), a large percentage of word-forms are ambiguous.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Correct grammatical tagging will reflect that "dogs" is here used as a verb, not as the more common plural noun.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Schools commonly teach that there are 9 parts of speech in English: noun, verb, article, adjective, preposition, pronoun, adverb, conjunction, and interjection.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] However, there are clearly many more categories and sub-categories.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] For nouns, the plural, possessive, and singular forms can be distinguished.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] In many languages words are also marked for their "case" (role as subject, object, etc.), grammatical gender, and so on; while verbs are marked for tense, aspect, and other things.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] In some tagging systems, different inflections of the same root word will get different parts of speech, resulting in a large number of tags.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, NN for singular common nouns, NNS for plural common nouns, NP for singular proper nouns (see the POS tags used in the Brown Corpus).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Other tagging systems use a smaller number of tags and ignore fine differences or model them as features somewhat independent from part-of-speech.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] In part-of-speech tagging by computer, it is typical to distinguish from 50 to 150 separate parts of speech for English.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Work on stochastic methods for tagging Koine Greek (DeRose 1990) has used over 1,000 parts of speech and found that about as many words were ambiguous in that language as in English.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] A morphosyntactic descriptor in the case of morphologically rich languages is commonly expressed using very short mnemonics, such as *Ncmsan* for Category = Noun, Type = common, Gender = masculine, Number = singular, Case = accusative, Animate = no.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] The most popular "tag set" for POS tagging for American English is probably the Penn tag set, developed in the Penn Treebank project.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] It is largely similar to the earlier Brown Corpus and LOB Corpus tag sets, though much smaller.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] In Europe, tag sets from the Eagles Guidelines see wide use and include versions for multiple languages.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] POS tagging work has been done in a variety of languages, and the set of POS tags used varies greatly with language.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Tags usually are designed to include overt morphological distinctions, although this leads to inconsistencies such as case-marking for pronouns but not nouns in English, and much larger cross-language differences.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] The tag sets for heavily inflected languages such as Greek and Latin can be very large; tagging *words* in agglutinative languages such as Inuit languages may be virtually impossible.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] At the other extreme, Petrov et al. have proposed a "universal" tag set, with 12 categories (for example, no subtypes of nouns, verbs, punctuation, and so on).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Whether a very small set of very broad tags or a much larger set of more precise ones is preferable, depends on the purpose at hand.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Automatic tagging is easier on smaller tag-sets.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Research on part-of-speech tagging has been closely tied to corpus linguistics.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] The first major corpus of English for computer analysis was the Brown Corpus developed at Brown University by Henry Kučera and W.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] It consists of about 1,000,000 words of running English prose text, made up of 500 samples from randomly chosen publications.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Each sample is 2,000 or more words (ending at the first sentence-end after 2,000 words, so that the corpus contains only complete sentences).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] The Brown Corpus was painstakingly "tagged" with part-of-speech markers over many years.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] A first approximation was done with a program by Greene and Rubin, which consisted of a huge handmade list of what categories could co-occur at all.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, article then noun can occur, but article then verb (arguably) cannot.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Its results were repeatedly reviewed and corrected by hand, and later users sent in errata so that by the late 70s the tagging was nearly perfect (allowing for some cases on which even human speakers might not agree).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] This corpus has been used for innumerable studies of word-frequency and of part-of-speech and inspired the development of similar "tagged" corpora in many other languages.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Statistics derived by analyzing it formed the basis for most later part-of-speech tagging systems, such as CLAWS and VOLSUNGA.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] However, by this time (2005) it has been superseded by larger corpora such as the 100 million word British National Corpus, even though larger corpora are rarely so thoroughly curated.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] For some time, part-of-speech tagging was considered an inseparable part of natural language processing, because there are certain cases where the correct part of speech cannot be decided without understanding the semantics or even the pragmatics of the context.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] This is extremely expensive, especially because analyzing the higher levels is much harder when multiple part-of-speech possibilities must be considered for each word.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] In the mid-1980s, researchers in Europe began to use hidden Markov models (HMMs) to disambiguate parts of speech, when working to tag the Lancaster-Oslo-Bergen Corpus of British English.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] HMMs involve counting cases (such as from the Brown Corpus) and making a table of the probabilities of certain sequences.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, once you've seen an article such as 'the', perhaps the next word is a noun 40% of the time, an adjective 40%, and a number 20%.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Knowing this, a program can decide that "can" in "the can" is far more likely to be a noun than a verb or a modal.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] The same method can, of course, be used to benefit from knowledge about the following words.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] More advanced ("higher-order") HMMs learn the probabilities not only of pairs but triples or even larger sequences.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] So, for example, if you've just seen a noun followed by a verb, the next item may be very likely a preposition, article, or noun, but much less likely another verb.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] When several ambiguous words occur together, the possibilities multiply.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] However, it is easy to enumerate every combination and to assign a relative probability to each one, by multiplying together the probabilities of each choice in turn.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] The combination with the highest probability is then chosen.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] The European group developed CLAWS, a tagging program that did exactly this and achieved accuracy in the 93–95% range.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] CLAWS pioneered the field of HMM-based part of speech tagging but was quite expensive since it enumerated all possibilities.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] It sometimes had to resort to backup methods when there were simply too many options (the Brown Corpus contains a case with 17 ambiguous words in a row, and there are words such as "still" that can represent as many as 7 distinct parts of speech.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] HMMs underlie the functioning of stochastic taggers and are used in various algorithms one of the most widely used being the bi-directional inference algorithm.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Church independently developed dynamic programming algorithms to solve the same problem in vastly less time.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Their methods were similar to the Viterbi algorithm known for some time in other fields.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] DeRose used a table of pairs, while Church used a table of triples and a method of estimating the values for triples that were rare or nonexistent in the Brown Corpus (an actual measurement of triple probabilities would require a much larger corpus).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Both methods achieved an accuracy of over 95%.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] DeRose's 1990 dissertation at Brown University included analyses of the specific error types, probabilities, and other related data, and replicated his work for Greek, where it proved similarly effective.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] These findings were surprisingly disruptive to the field of natural language processing.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] The accuracy reported was higher than the typical accuracy of very sophisticated algorithms that integrated part of speech choice with many higher levels of linguistic analysis: syntax, morphology, semantics, and so on.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] CLAWS, DeRose's and Church's methods did fail for some of the known cases where semantics is required, but those proved negligibly rare.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] This convinced many in the field that part-of-speech tagging could usefully be separated from the other levels of processing; this, in turn, simplified the theory and practice of computerized language analysis and encouraged researchers to find ways to separate other pieces as well.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Markov Models became the standard method for the part-of-speech assignment.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] The methods already discussed involve working from a pre-existing corpus to learn tag probabilities.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] It is, however, also possible to bootstrap using "unsupervised" tagging.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Unsupervised tagging techniques use an untagged corpus for their training data and produce the tagset by induction.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] That is, they observe patterns in word use, and derive part-of-speech categories themselves.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] For example, statistics readily reveal that "the", "a", and "an" occur in similar contexts, while "eat" occurs in very different ones.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] With sufficient iteration, similarity classes of words emerge that are remarkably similar to those human linguists would expect; and the differences themselves sometimes suggest valuable new insights.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] These two categories can be further subdivided into rule-based, stochastic, and neural approaches.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Some current major algorithms for part-of-speech tagging include the Viterbi algorithm, Brill tagger, Constraint Grammar, and the Baum-Welch algorithm (also known as the forward-backward algorithm).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Hidden Markov model and visible Markov model taggers can both be implemented using the Viterbi algorithm.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] The rule-based Brill tagger is unusual in that it learns a set of rule patterns, and then applies those patterns rather than optimizing a statistical quantity.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Many machine learning methods have also been applied to the problem of POS tagging.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Methods such as SVM, maximum entropy classifier, perceptron, and nearest-neighbor have all been tried, and most can achieve accuracy above 95%.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] A direct comparison of several methods is reported (with references) at the ACL Wiki.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] This comparison uses the Penn tag set on some of the Penn Treebank data, so the results are directly comparable.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] However, many significant taggers are not included (perhaps because of the labor involved in reconfiguring them for this particular dataset).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] Thus, it should not be assumed that the results reported here are the best that can be achieved with a given approach; nor even the best that *have* been achieved with a given approach.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/part-of-speech-tagging] In 2014, a paper reported using the structure regularization method for part-of-speech tagging, achieving 97.36% on a standard benchmark dataset.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Compare speech segmentation, the process of dividing speech into linguistically meaningful portions.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Word segmentation is the problem of dividing a string of written language into its component words.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] In English and many other languages using some form of the Latin alphabet, the space is a good approximation of a word divider (word delimiter), although this concept has limits because of the variability with which languages emically regard collocations and compounds.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] In contrast, German compound nouns show less orthographic variation, with solidification being a stronger norm.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] However, the equivalent to the word space character is not found in all written scripts, and without it word segmentation is a difficult problem.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Languages which do not have a trivial word segmentation process include Chinese, Japanese, where sentences but not words are delimited, Thai and Lao, where phrases and sentences but not words are delimited, and Vietnamese, where syllables but not words are delimited.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] In some writing systems however, such as the Ge'ez script used for Amharic and Tigrinya among other languages, words are explicitly delimited (at least historically) with a non-whitespace character.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] The Unicode Consortium has published a *Standard Annex on Text Segmentation*, exploring the issues of segmentation in multiscript texts.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Word splitting may also refer to the process of hyphenation.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Some scholars have suggested that modern Chinese should be written in word segmentation, with spaces between words like written English.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Because there are ambiguous texts where only the author knows the intended meaning.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] For example, "美国会不同意。" may mean "美国 会 不同意。" (The US will not agree.) or "美 国会 不同意。" (The US Congress does not agree).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] For more details, see Chinese word-segmented writing.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Intent segmentation is the problem of dividing written words into keyphrases (2 or more group of words).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] In English and all other languages the core intent or desire is identified and become the corner-stone of the keyphrase Intent segmentation.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Core product/service, idea, action & or thought anchor the keyphrase.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Sentence segmentation is the problem of dividing a string of written language into its component sentences.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] In English and some other languages, using punctuation, particularly the full stop/period character is a reasonable approximation.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] However even in English this problem is not trivial due to the use of the full stop character for abbreviations, which may or may not also terminate a sentence.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] For example, *Mr.* is not its own sentence in "*Mr.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Smith went to the shops in Jones Street."* When processing plain text, tables of abbreviations that contain periods can help prevent incorrect assignment of sentence boundaries.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] As with word segmentation, not all written languages contain punctuation characters that are useful for approximating sentence boundaries.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Topic analysis consists of two main tasks: topic identification and text segmentation.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] While the first is a simple classification of a specific text, the latter case implies that a document may contain multiple topics, and the task of computerized text segmentation may be to discover these topics automatically and segment the text accordingly.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] The topic boundaries may be apparent from section titles and paragraphs.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] In other cases, one needs to use techniques similar to those used in document classification.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] It is also needed in topic detection and tracking systems and text summarizing problems.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Many different approaches have been tried: e.g.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] HMM, lexical chains, passage similarity using word co-occurrence, clustering, topic modeling, etc.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] It is quite an ambiguous task – people evaluating the text segmentation systems often differ in topic boundaries.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Hence, text segment evaluation is also a challenging problem.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Processes may be required to segment text into segments besides mentioned, including morphemes (a task usually called morphological analysis) or paragraphs.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Automatic segmentation is the problem in natural language processing of implementing a computer process to segment text.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] When punctuation and similar clues are not consistently available, the segmentation task often requires fairly non-trivial techniques, such as statistical decision-making, large dictionaries, as well as consideration of syntactic and semantic constraints.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Effective natural language processing systems and text segmentation tools usually operate on text in specific domains and sources.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] As an example, processing text used in medical records is a very different problem than processing news articles or real estate advertisements.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] The process of developing text segmentation tools starts with collecting a large corpus of text in an application domain.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/text-segmentation] Some text segmentation systems take advantage of any markup like HTML and know document formats like PDF to provide additional evidence for sentence and paragraph boundaries.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] In information retrieval, **tf–idf** (**term frequency–inverse document frequency**, **TF*IDF**, **TFIDF**, **TF–IDF**, or **Tf–idf**) is a measure of importance of a word to a document in a collection or corpus, adjusted for the fact that some words appear more frequently in general.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] Like the bag-of-words model, it models a document as a multiset of words, without word order.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] It is a refinement over the simple bag-of-words model, by allowing the weight of words to depend on the rest of the corpus.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] It was often used as a weighting factor in searches of information retrieval, text mining, and user modeling.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] A survey conducted in 2015 showed that 83% of text-based recommender systems in digital libraries used tf–idf.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] Variations of the tf–idf weighting scheme were often used by search engines as a central tool in scoring and ranking a document's relevance given a user query.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] One of the simplest ranking functions is computed by summing the tf–idf for each query term; many more sophisticated ranking functions are variants of this simple model.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] We see that "Romeo", "Falstaff", and "salad" appears in very few plays, so seeing these words, one could get a good idea as to which play it might be.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] In contrast, "good" and "sweet" appears in every play and are completely uninformative as to which play it is.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] A formula that aims to define the importance of a keyword or phrase within a document or a web page.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] where *f**t*,*d* is the *raw count* of a term in a document, i.e., the number of times that term t occurs in document d.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] Note the denominator is simply the total number of terms in document *d* (counting each occurrence of the same term separately).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] The **inverse document frequency** is a measure of how much information the word provides, i.e., how common or rare it is across all documents.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] A high weight in tf–idf is reached by a high term frequency (in the given document) and a low document frequency of the term in the whole collection of documents; the weights hence tend to filter out common terms.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] Since the ratio inside the idf's log function is always greater than or equal to 1, the value of idf (and tf–idf) is greater than or equal to 0.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] As a term appears in more documents, the ratio inside the logarithm approaches 1, bringing the idf and tf–idf closer to 0.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] Idf was introduced as "term specificity" by Karen Spärck Jones in a 1972 paper.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] Although it has worked well as a heuristic, its theoretical foundations have been troublesome for at least three decades afterward, with many researchers trying to find information theoretic justifications for it.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] Spärck Jones's own explanation did not propose much theory, aside from a connection to Zipf's law.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] Namely, the inverse document frequency is the logarithm of "inverse" relative document frequency.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] This probabilistic interpretation in turn takes the same form as that of self-information.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] However, applying such information-theoretic notions to problems in information retrieval leads to problems when trying to define the appropriate event spaces for the required probability distributions: not only documents need to be taken into account, but also queries and terms.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] Both term frequency and inverse document frequency can be formulated in terms of information theory; it helps to understand why their product has a meaning in terms of joint informational content of a document.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] In terms of notation, ${\cal {D}}$ and ${\cal {T}}$ are "random variables" corresponding to respectively draw a document or a term.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] This expression shows that summing the Tf–idf of all possible terms and documents recovers the mutual information between documents and term taking into account all the specificities of their joint distribution.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] Each Tf–idf hence carries the "bit of information" attached to a term x document pair.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] Tf–idf is closely related to the negative logarithmically transformed *p*-value from a one-tailed formulation of Fisher's exact test when the underlying corpus documents satisfy certain idealized assumptions.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] More recently, tf–idf variants were shown to arise as components in the test statistic of a penalized likelihood-ratio test for word burstiness based on a beta-binomial statistical language model.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] In this framework, the null hypothesis models term occurrences using a binomial distribution, while the alternative hypothesis models word burstiness using a beta-binomial distribution with a gamma-distributed penalty term placed on the beta-binomial precision parameter.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] The resulting test statistic contains the tf–idf variants binary term frequency–inverse document frequency (btf–idf) and term frequency–inverse collection frequency (tf–icf), thereby establishing a direct connection between tf–idf family term-weighting schemes and statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] In its raw frequency form, tf is just the frequency of the "this" for each document.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] In each document, the word "this" appears once; but as the document 2 has more words, its relative frequency is smaller.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] An idf is constant per corpus, and **accounts** for the ratio of documents that include the word "this".
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] In this case, we have a corpus of two documents and all of them include the word "this".
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] So tf–idf is zero for the word "this", which implies that the word is not very informative as it appears in all documents.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] The idea behind tf–idf also applies to entities other than terms.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] In 1998, the concept of idf was applied to citations.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] The authors argued that "if a very uncommon citation is shared by two documents, this should be weighted more highly than a citation made by a large number of documents".
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] In addition, tf–idf was applied to "visual words" with the purpose of conducting object matching in videos, and entire sentences.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] However, the concept of tf–idf did not prove to be more effective in all cases than a plain tf scheme (without idf).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] When tf–idf was applied to citations, researchers could find no improvement over a simple citation-count weight that had no idf component.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] A number of term-weighting schemes have derived from tf–idf.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] One of them is TF–PDF (term frequency * proportional document frequency).
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] TF–PDF was introduced in 2001 in the context of identifying emerging topics in the media.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] The PDF component measures the difference of how often a term occurs in different domains.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] In TF–IDuF, idf is not calculated based on the document corpus that is to be searched or recommended.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] Instead, idf is calculated on users' personal document collections.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] The authors report that TF–IDuF was equally effective as tf–idf but could also be applied in situations when, e.g., a user modeling system has no access to a global document corpus.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] The DELTA TF-IDF derivative uses the difference in importance of a term across two specific classes, like positive and negative sentiment.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] For example, it can assign a high score to a word like "excellent" in positive reviews and a low score to the same word in negative reviews.
[src:keyphrase-extraction/tf-idf] This helps identify words that strongly indicate the sentiment of a document, potentially leading to improved accuracy in text classification tasks.
